Pass 2 — End-User Click-Through

  Where I got confused

  1. Register CTA copy doesn't match the action I took.
  Landing page CTA says "Start your franchise →". I click it and land on a page headlined "Join the league. Pick your team." Those are two different framings. "Start your franchise" implies creating and owning a team. "Join the league" implies joining something that already exists First thing I see after clicking "Start" is join-flavored copy. Maybe we should consider a "Start your legacy" messaging? then let the user decide if they want to join an existing league or create a new one?

  **How to fix (UX-017):** In `app/register/page.tsx` (or whatever component the CTA lands on), update the page headline and sub-copy to match the "franchise / management" framing established by REBRAND-001/002. The register page should continue the "Start your franchise" journey — use "Create your account to get started" or "Join PWHL GM" as the headline, not "Join the league. Pick your team." which implies joining an existing entity. File: `app/register/page.tsx` headline `<h1>` and sub-copy paragraph.

  **Covered by:** UX-017 (net-new)

  ---

  2. "My Matchup" goes to a blank page with no escape hatch.
  Dashboard card: I click "My Matchup →." I land on /team/[id]/matchup showing only: "No scoring period is active or upcoming. Check back when the season is underway." No link back to the admin panel. No explanation of what a "scoring period" is or when one will start. No suggestion of what to do next. Dead end.

  **How to fix:** The empty state on the matchup page needs a page-specific message and at least one next-action link. Pre-draft: "Draft hasn't happened yet. Set your lineup once the draft is complete." with a link back to the league overview. Post-draft / pre-season: "The season starts soon. Draft is complete — check back on [draft date link] to start scoring." Use `EmptyState.tsx` `cta` prop. File: `app/team/[teamId]/matchup/page.tsx`.

  **Covered by:** UX-016 (which already calls out the matchup page empty state specifically).

